<br>
   He sat down and rested a minute before recollecting himself and trudging inland, towards a high peak at the center of the island.  The land was a sparse forest alive with birds and reptiles of various types.  Some of the snakes were brightly colored and he steered clear of them, wisely heeding their natural warnings.  No other apparent threats were to be seen, however he could not shake the feeling that he was being watched and on more than one occasion he sensed a follower.  In spite of several devious attempts to double back and ambush this perceived presence, he never saw nor heard anything.<br>
<br>
   After about an hour, the shadowknight reached the base of the cone, for he saw now thats what it was, a dead volcano as ancient as his home city.  He almost immediately came upon a small cave, and cautiously peered in.  Nothing seemed alive within its confines, however a small spring gurgled inside.  He now knew he at least had something to drink.  He made this his new home.  He counted the the months by the passing moon and although the sense of another presence was constant, Sanchez didnt see another living soul for almost a year.   <br>
<br>
   On that day, he awoke from his dreams (always of her) to the sound of music, sad and lonely but nonetheless very elf like.  He went outside following the sound of the music, carefully avoiding the snares he had set to trap small animals.  The sound led him to the beach, where he saw a half elf sitting amongst a large amount of flotsom and jetsom(obviously the remnants of a ship), strumming an instrument called a git-fiddle (he had never seen one in this life and didn't know how he knew its name).  With a snarl he lept from a concealing bush and cleft the infidel with his great sword, leaving a viscous wound.  The bard, bleeding and obviously startled, jumped and attempted to flee.  Calling upon the power of Innoruuk, Sanchez froze the half-mans heart with a touch and watched as it fell lifeless to the ground.  Searching the corpse he found a few coins (worthless here) and a few rations.  Nothing else of any use.  His eyes then instinctively looked behind where he sensed the presence and then fell upon the discarded git-fiddle, undamaged in the brief but violent assault.  Walking over he picked it up and sat down.  Unknown as to how he knew, he began to strum it, playing a song.  He began to sing, the words never been heard by his ears, nonetheless he knew it by heart and also knew by whom it had been written.  A human, it's name was....Robert!  He paused in contemplation, as he also realized that this man had never walked in Norrath.  Not uinderstanding, but drawn just the same he resumed the song:<br>
<br>
<br>
 *If the sun refused to shine,<br>
 I would still be loving you.<br>
 When mountains crumble to the sea,<br>
 There will still be you and me.<br>
<br>
Kind woman, I give you my all,<br>
Kind woman, nothing more.<br>
<br>
Little drops of rain whisper of the pain,<br>
Tears of loves lost in the days gone by.<br>
My love is strong, with you there is no wrong,<br>
Together we shall go until we die.<br>
My, my, my,<br>
An inspiration is what you are to me,<br>
Inspiration, look see.<br>
<br>
And so today, my world it smiles,<br>
Your hand in mine, we walk the miles,<br>
Thanks to you it will be done,<br>
For you to me are the only one.<br>
Happiness, no more be sad,<br>
Happiness....I'm glad.*<br>
<br>
As he finished, a tear fell gently from hjis eye, knowing he would never leave this island in this body.  With nothing but his memories, a git-fiddle and some strange presence he could neither see nor comprehend he was doomed here on this tiny island to live out his days.<br>
